 haiku by Bashо̄ and Issa. In the twentieth century, Japan went through its darkest years. But out of the trauma of militarism, war, devastation, and defeat came outstanding fiction by Dazai Osamu and Natsume Sо̄seki, as well as avant-garde poetry by Yoshioka Minoru and Ayukawa Nobuo. In recent decades, contemporary optimism has produced writing that breaks new literary ground without forgetting the past: experimental fiction by Kurahashi Yumiko and poetry about everyday life by Takahashi Mutsuo.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Asian / Japanese.2bisacsh  aJapan.  aJapanese fiction.  aJapanese poetry.  aanthologies.  aliterature.  atranslation.1 aBashō, Matsuo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIssa, Kobayashi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLowitz, Leza, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMacmillan, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMinoru, Yoshioka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMutsuo, Takahashi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNijō, Lady, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNobuo, Ayukawa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOketani, Shogo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOsamu, Dazai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSelland, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShikibu, Lady Murasaki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStewart, Frank, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSōseki, Natsume, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat